{
  "slug": "is-red-one-the-worst-movie-of-the-year-plus-a-real-pain-with",
  "title": "Is ‘Red One’ the Worst Movie of the Year? Plus: ‘A Real Pain’ With Jesse Eisenberg!",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Joanna Robinson"
  ],
  "published": "2024-11-19",
  "runtimeMin": 101,
  "format": "Sean and Joanna try to work out who Red One is even for, detour into whether the Hollywood Christmas movie still exists, then turn to A Real Pain and the crowded Best Supporting Actor race before trading five favorite two-handers each. Then Jesse Eisenberg on directing A Real Pain.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Red One’",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Red One",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Jake Kasdan's big Amazon tentpole, written by Fast & Furious hand Chris Morgan: Santa (J.K. Simmons) is kidnapped and his head of security (Dwayne Johnson) is paired with a cynical tracker (Chris Evans) to get him back. Sean and Joanna both saw it with a drink and still couldn't answer the only question that mattered: who is this for? Too sweary and violent for kids, too juvenile for adults. Johnson plays it like a war drama, Evans misses the needle between dirtbag and likable, and only Kristofer Hivju's Krampus and a barely-used Bonnie Hunt seem to know what movie they're in."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Does the Hollywood Christmas movie still exist?",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Elf",
          "year": 2003,
          "note": "Sean's pick for the last title to really enter the canon, the one you watch at five and keep forever."
        },
        {
          "title": "Love Actually",
          "year": 2003,
          "note": "The other 2003 movie he'd put in the canon, though as a rom-com it doesn't reach kids the same way, and it has that body-double subplot."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Santa Clause",
          "year": 1994,
          "note": "The model Red One seemed to want and miss: a crowd-pleaser aimed squarely at kids five years younger than them."
        },
        {
          "title": "Home Alone",
          "year": 1990,
          "note": "The 90s Christmas-movie boom whose tail Red One is still chasing."
        },
        {
          "title": "Miracle on 34th Street",
          "year": 1947,
          "note": "The old-Hollywood Christmas they grew up rerunning once a year and loving because it felt special."
        },
        {
          "title": "It's a Wonderful Life",
          "year": 1946,
          "note": "Same canon: decades-old movies rerun on network TV, back when scarcity made them feel special."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Holiday",
          "year": 2006,
          "note": "Sean thinks it's half a good movie (the Kate Winslet and Jack Black video-store half) and a failure otherwise. People watch it every year anyway."
        },
        {
          "title": "Hot Frosty",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "The Netflix Lacey Chabert movie where she falls for a snowman, Sean's exhibit for how disposable the genre has gotten now that Netflix and Hallmark pump out a dozen-plus a year."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘A Real Pain’",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "A Real Pain",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Jesse Eisenberg's second feature as director: cousins David (Eisenberg) and Benji (Kieran Culkin) take a Holocaust-heritage tour of Poland to honor their late grandmother. Sean's favorite kind of sad dramedy (Billy Wilder, Hal Ashby, Woody Allen tonality) and a rare cousins two-hander. Joanna found it deliberately agitating, better in the thinking-about than the watching; Culkin is essentially in his Succession register, and the dinner-scene push-in is one of the tensest things she's sat through. The movie ends where Benji began."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The Best Supporting Actor race",
      "note": "Sean's rundown of the field",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Gladiator II",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Denzel Washington as Macrinus, the best part of the movie and, unlike Culkin, not just doing Denzel things. Sean can see a third career Oscar."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Brutalist",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Guy Pearce, likely one of Sean's favorite performances of the year: the argument that a decades-long chameleon who's never won deserves it more than Culkin doing Culkin."
        },
        {
          "title": "Anora",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Yura Borisov, supporting acting done right: Sean Baker's cutaways to his face set up the final act. Real supporting, unlike Culkin's category fraud."
        },
        {
          "title": "Sing Sing",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Clarence Maclin, playing a version of himself; both loved it and think the strong real-life narrative could push him into the front-runners."
        },
        {
          "title": "Conclave",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Stanley Tucci, a good performance that maybe lacks the one big scene to carry him."
        },
        {
          "title": "September 5",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "John Magaro (really the lead) and Peter Sarsgaard, both campaigning in supporting."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Room Next Door",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "John Turturro, one okay, overwritten scene that the betting markets somehow rate highly. Sean and Joanna are both confused by it."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Apprentice",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Jeremy Strong as Roy Cohn: if any Succession actor gets in, Sean argues it should be the one who's never the same twice."
        },
        {
          "title": "A Different Man",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Adam Pearson, a movie Sean liked but hasn't had much chance to talk about beyond having Sebastian Stan on."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Piano Lesson",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Ray Fisher was the big surprise for Sean, who didn't know Cyborg had it in him; due another crack."
        },
        {
          "title": "Challengers",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Josh O'Connor, slight category fraud but the best part of the movie; the pair formally apologize for skipping it on Friday."
        },
        {
          "title": "Wicked",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Jonathan Bailey, exactly what he needs to be, but Sean doesn't see the nomination happening."
        },
        {
          "title": "A Complete Unknown",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Edward Norton as Pete Seeger, the showy historical transformation the Academy tends to reward."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Fire Inside",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Brian Tyree Henry, in the Jennifer Lawrence movie once called Red, White and Blue, so forgotten Joanna couldn't produce the new title."
        },
        {
          "title": "Nosferatu",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Bill Skarsgård, the monster performance Sean would most like to see honored, the kind they never do."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "list",
      "heading": "Five favorite two-handers",
      "note": "one list each, worst-to-best on air",
      "picks": [
        {
          "title": "Swiss Army Man",
          "year": 2016,
          "by": "Joanna Robinson",
          "note": "No. 5: a clear-as-day two-hander she's rewatched a bunch."
        },
        {
          "title": "Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid",
          "year": 1969,
          "by": "Joanna Robinson",
          "note": "No. 4: the obvious one, and it has to be there."
        },
        {
          "title": "Road to Morocco",
          "year": 1942,
          "by": "Joanna Robinson",
          "note": "No. 3: a Mallory Rubin-style franchise smuggle for the whole Bob Hope / Bing Crosby Road series; Morocco is the best one, if you can look past what's dated."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Banshees of Inisherin",
          "year": 2022,
          "by": "Joanna Robinson",
          "note": "No. 2: the movie she's thought about most in the last several years, even with Barry Keoghan and Kerry Condon in support."
        },
        {
          "title": "Withnail & I",
          "year": 1987,
          "by": "Joanna Robinson",
          "note": "No. 1: Richard E. Grant and Paul McGann; the best version of the antique/stolid pairing, and a good companion to A Real Pain."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Nice Guys",
          "year": 2016,
          "by": "Sean Fennessey",
          "note": "No. 5: Gosling and Crowe; the best movie he's ever seen on a plane, and maybe one of the last of its kind."
        },
        {
          "title": "Thelma & Louise",
          "year": 1991,
          "by": "Sean Fennessey",
          "note": "No. 4: Sarandon and Davis; friendship as loyalty and tentativeness, the supporting men kept small."
        },
        {
          "title": "Sweet Smell of Success",
          "year": 1957,
          "by": "Sean Fennessey",
          "note": "No. 3: Tony Curtis and Burt Lancaster, two men who hate each other; the poster hangs over his desk at home."
        },
        {
          "title": "Paper Moon",
          "year": 1973,
          "by": "Sean Fennessey",
          "note": "No. 2: Ryan and Tatum O'Neal, con man and kid, just reissued in 4K by Criterion."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Lighthouse",
          "year": 2019,
          "by": "Sean Fennessey",
          "note": "No. 1: Pattinson and Dafoe; he walked out genuinely nauseous and thinks about it all the time."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "Jesse Eisenberg on ‘A Real Pain’",
      "guest": "Jesse Eisenberg on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "A Real Pain",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Started as a story about two friends visiting a supposed radical who'd sold out to a tourism company in Mongolia; it stalled until a banner ad for 'Auschwitz Tours (with lunch)' turned the friends into cousins and gave the angst a backdrop. Cousins, not siblings, because a dead grandmother lets the pair choose whether to keep existing as a pair."
        },
        {
          "title": "When You Finish Saving the World",
          "year": 2022,
          "note": "His first feature. Sean was the rare interviewer who'd actually seen it. Same interest in characters searching for meaning while stymied by their own self-indulgence."
        },
        {
          "title": "The End of the Tour",
          "year": 2015,
          "note": "The two-hander he consciously worked to avoid echoing (down to both his characters being named David), while borrowing its trick of keeping the tour in the background as metaphor."
        },
        {
          "title": "Never Rarely Sometimes Always",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "Eliza Hittman's film, the last thing that shocked him; adoration followed by 'do I have that in me?' He reached out, became friends, and is helping get her next movie made."
        },
        {
          "title": "Now You See Me",
          "year": 2013,
          "note": "The one time he engineered a persona: a confident, arrogant guy who's the opposite of him. He'd just finished the third one, his favorite sets to stand on."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
